title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Bodyguard .380 two-tone, stainless, stippled
location: Briargate/ Colorado Springs, Colorado Springs, Colorado
postcontent:
I have a Smith and Wesson Bodyguard .380
It has been polished for that custom two tone look.  Slide is stainless steel. 
The grip is fully stippled to give it a real aggressive grip making it easier to hold on to. It  noticeably improved my accuracy. 

This gun is a true double action which makes it much better (in my opinion) for  ankle carry.  It has a long trigger pull like most pocket .380s but because it's a true double action if there is a misfire you can keep pulling the trigger on the same round until it goes off. I've never had it misfire but in an emergency situation you don't want to have to rack the slide to reset the firing pin before shooting again.  

I owned the Ruger LCP and I hated it. I love this gun and would trust my life with it over an lcp any day.  The biggest differences is the trigger pull, the double action,  slide lock, and safety. All these things make it a better gun.  

This gun has been my daily carry but has only seen a couple hundred rounds. And I clean it regularly. It shoots flawlessly and the laser functions well. 

Comes with two magazines. One has an extended tail piece so you can get all three figures on it.   Ankle holster  included. 

Also has a clip installed making it very easy to clip it on anything. I've even carried it in a pair of gym shorts. 

Looking for trade or cash.  Cash price is $380 FIRM. Buyer pays transfer. 

Text or email Tim REDACTED

title: For Sale:  M1831 .52 CAL HALL BREECH LOAD RIFLE - CIVIL WAR USE
postcontent:
CONFEDERATE  CIVIL WAR USE   

Additional pictures available.

The first American Breech Loading Rifle.  These rifles (converted to percussion as this one was, saw action by the Confederate States during the Civil War – Flayderman.

19,680 Hall Rifles were produced mainly at Harpers Ferry by 1840 - Flayderman.  

23,500 rifles produced by 1842 mainly at Harpers Ferry Arsenal - http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hall_rifle .

Rifling extends to within 1 ½ inches of the muzzle apparently to allow for muzzle loading if necessary – Flayderman and Reilly.

Iron mountings and the barrel were finished with brown lacquer – Flayderman and Reilly.

Oil finished black walnut stock – Reilly.

A large number of these rifles were in the various Southern Arsenals at the outbreak of the Civil War and were altered from flintlock to percussion by the Confederate States.  Flayderman

During the War of 1812 fifteen year old American Schoolboys volunteered service and with the Hall Rifle successfully defended a bridge in 1814 during the Siege of Plattsburgh, repelling advancing British troops.

HISTORY:  This rifle was designed by John Harris Hall who was born in Portland, Maine on January 4, 1781.  He died at the age of 60 in Moberly, Missouri which is 933 miles to the west of Harpers Ferry.  Hall worked in his father's tannery until setting up his own woodworking and boat building shop in 1810 where he tinkered with guns in his spare time. He took an interest in firearms during militia service and focused on increasing the rapidity of loading.  On May 21, 1811, Hall patented a single shot, breech-loading rifle in collusion with Washington, D.C. architect, Dr. William Thornton.  

He began manufacturing his new rifles at the rate of 50 per year until the Ordnance Corps (United States Army) ordered 200 rifles in December 1814.  He regretfully turned down the contract because he was unable to meet the Army delivery deadline of 1815. Hall recognized individually fitted parts as the factor slowing rifle production, and adapted his breech-loading design to the “uniformity principle,” widely known as interchangeable parts.  Hall proposed the concept of interchangeable parts to the Army in June, 1816,[1] and earned a contract for 1,000 of the "Model of 1819" Hall rifles from the War Department with interchangeable parts being the chief condition.  To fulfill it, Hall spent more than five years (and $150,000 of government funds) at Harpers Ferry Arsenal, where he occupied an old sawmill on a small island in the Shenandoah River called Virginius Island. 

Hall's contract for 1,000 rifles was completed in 1825.  When a three-man committee deployed by the US Ordnance Department to verify Hall’s process in fulfilling his rifle contract visited Harpers Ferry, they were floored by his results, and especially the machines. They lauded Hall’s “system, in the manufacture of small arms, [as] entirely novel,” and one which could yield “the most beneficial results to the Country, especially, if carried into effect on a large scale”.[2]

A trial was devised to test the rate of fire of Hall's breech-loading rifles in comparison to muzzle loading rifles and Army-issue muzzle loading muskets. A company of 38 men were given 10 minutes to load and fire at targets 100 yards distant.   The company scored 164 HITS (33% of the 464 shots fired) with conventional muzzle-loading rifles, and 208 HITS (25% of the 845 shots fired) with the faster loading, but less accurate, army-issue smooth-bore muskets, in comparison to 430 HITS (36% of the 1198 shots fired) with Hall's rifles.[1]

Hall's rifle design worked so well as to undergo minimal change through the end of the Model 1819’s run in 1853.  By 1842, 23,500 rifles and 13,682 Hall-North carbines had been produced, most at Harper's ferry, earning Hall nearly $40,000 in royalty and patent-licensing fees. The men who had learned Hall's methods of interchangeable parts while working at Harper's Ferry (most notably Christian Sharps) went on to apply those methods to production of the Sharps rifles shoes, watches, clocks, bicycles, clothing, rubber goods, and, later, automobiles. 

As regards Christian Sharps a reference states:  Sharps accepted an entry level position at the Harpers Ferry Arsenal in the 1830s working as a filer. While at Harpers Ferry, Sharps was introduced to the Hall rifle, an early breech-loader, and worked for its inventor, Captain John H. Hall. Sharps also became versed in the manufacture of weapons with fully interchangeable parts.  Hall's methods transformed the United States from an economy of workshop craftsmen to a nation of industrialized mass production.

Selling a Smith&Wesson model 39 (not 39-2) 9mm semi-automatic with two single stack magazines. Steel slide with aluminum frame and original wood grips. 

This weapon has a pretty cool history. Was the issue sidearm to commanding officers of naval special warfare during the Vietnam war. title: For Sale/Trade:  Taurus PT-92 Stanless
postcontent:
Taurus PT-92 in stainless steel, pre-decocker, used, comes with one mag. $285 OBO. All trades welcomed.

I hate it when I buy a gun off of armslist and it has problems the seller didn't tell me about. So as a service to you, here are any and all of the issues with this gun. 

The frame and slide is scratched and nicked from regular use, not a brand new gun. I've fired over 600 rounds through it, so again not a new gun. I've only used this one mag the whole time I've had this piece, so it no longer locks back on the last round. You'll need to probably buy a new mag to fix that. This has no decocker like the newer PT-92s. This doesn't suggest better quality like a pre-lock Smith and Wesson, this just means that you don't have a decocking option. 

Good things about the gun.

The slide and action is buttery smooth and well broken in. Excellent DA/SA trigger, clean 5~6 lbs break in SA and a smooth DA pull. The bullets go where the sights are, at 15 yds you'll hit what you're aiming at. This thing will eat everything you feed it. Match grade ammo, steel cased ammo, JHP, the gun doesn't care. The mechanism and barrel are in good condition and this gun still has plenty of life in it. Mags and parts are easy to find. Many parts interchange with the Beretta 92fs. Satisfaction guaranteed or I refund your money/gun back!

title: For Sale:  Armalite AR-180A
postcontent:
1960s Sterling England AR-180A (Yes, original A, not B) Manufactured in Costa Mesa, California. 

Rifle is all original with adjustable carrying strap; chambered in .223. Fits 21 rounds: 20 round mag + 1 in the chamber. Rifle has quick-detach scope and a folding stock. Full length: 38 1/4 inches, folded length: 28 7/8 inches. Trigger pull is military style, hard and solid, feels natural even when you have only fired it once or twice (Have had several buddies and the girlfriend fire it). Charging handle is on the RIGHT, not centered.

Scope is original Japan licenses Armalite, quick-detach, 20 mm, 2.75x optical zoom with blank cross hair (no hashmarks). It has a top turret with a regular side adjustment (Not technically turreted). Scope has an aperture below it allowing for use of iron sights when it is attached. When we meet in person I will demonstrate all working actions this rifle has. 

Here's how I figured the price. Standard new AR style rifle currently sells for anywhere from $800-$1000 at Cabelas. This is older, but it has a lot of historic value being one of the first AR-180A Pre-Patent rifles from the Costa Mesa Facility. The scope is an easy $300-$400 because it is a quick-detach (It literally takes about 2-3 seconds to detach and re-attach) with an iron sight space.
